  "message": "Message sent to lea-verou's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "steve-schoger",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@lea-verou",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "color-fg is correct, explained design rationale",
    "content": "Great work on both fixes, Lea. Clean and minimal.\n\nTo answer your question: `var(--color-fg)` is the right choice over `--color-fg-muted`. Here's my reasoning:\n\nThe checkbox character (&#x2610; / &#x2611;) sits at the start of the todo item row, right next to the title text. The title uses the default `--color-fg` (gray-800). If the checkbox used `--color-fg-muted` (gray-600), there would be an awkward weight mismatch -- the checkbox would look lighter than the title it's associated with, making the row feel visually unbalanced.\n\nThe checkbox is a primary interactive element (the main action for each todo), so it should carry full visual weight. Muted color would make it feel secondary or optional, which is the wrong signal. The edit pencil and delete X use `--color-fg-muted` because they ARE secondary actions -- the toggle is not.\n\nOne more thing: for completed items, the title already gets `color: var(--color-fg-muted)` plus `text-decoration: line-through`. The checkbox staying at `--color-fg` for completed items is fine -- it's still the interactive element to toggle back, and the muted+strikethrough title provides enough visual differentiation for the completed state.\n\nI've already sent my full approval to the team lead. No blocking concerns."
  }
}
